ed view resembling the domes and towers of Sacré-Cœur. The bottle stands in front of the architecture, its cap and black label aligned over the glowing city scene.\n\nThe woman reappears in a closer view at the vanity. She holds the square Arpège bottle upright in one hand, label facing outward, while her other hand smooths or rubs perfume onto the inside of her wrist. A white vase and pink flowers sit behind the bottle. She lifts her perfumed wrist toward her face, bringing her hand near her mouth and cheek, as if inhaling the scent or savouring it. Her pearl bracelet is visible at the edge of the frame, and the bottle remains steady in her other hand.\n\nThe imagery blends again to a large Arpège bottle placed against a golden Paris skyline. The Eiffel Tower is now a hazy silhouette on the left, with the bottle on the right. The bottle’s black cap and dark front label contrast with the glowing amber liquid and sunlit background.\n\nA formal evening scene appears. A young adult man in a black tuxedo stands with his back and side toward the viewer, facing a blonde young adult woman. She wears a peach or rose-coloured dress with soft, ruffled or gathered details at the shoulders and bodice. Her hair is full and curled, and she holds a tall champagne flute. They stand near open French doors, with a balcony railing and a dim Paris view beyond; the Eiffel Tower is faintly visible outside. The woman looks toward the man, then turns her head slightly away, holding her glass close to her chest. The man also holds a champagne flute, his posture attentive and formal.\n\nThe view widens to include the elegant room around them: white-paned doors open onto the balcony, peach curtains hang to the right, and a leafy plant sits near a framed picture on the wall. The couple remains near the doorway, still facing one another in quiet conversation or shared attention. Finally, a large image of the Arpège perfume bottle appears on the right side of the scene, superimposed over the roo